No external template is needed – each node has this table in its code. When the node reads the binary string, it uses these hard‑coded offsets to extract individual channels or hormones.

2. From Binary to Cryptographic Hash (Fingerprint)
The entire 163,860‑byte string is fed into SHA‑256 as one contiguous block. The resulting 32‑byte hash is the fingerprint. This hash is content‑dependent: changing a single microvolt in channel 3, sample 1200 changes the hash completely.

The hash does not preserve the structure – you cannot recover which byte corresponds to which channel from the hash alone. The hash is only used as an identifier and as input to HKDF for frequency derivation.

